# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stochastic-processes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This motion pattern typically consists of random fluctuations in a particle's position inside a fluid sub-domain, followed by a relocation to another sub-domain.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Each relocation is followed by more fluctuations within the new closed volume.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This pattern describes a fluid at thermal equilibrium, defined by a given temperature.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Within such a fluid, there exists no preferential direction of flow (as in transport phenomena).
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] More specifically, the fluid's overall linear and angular momenta remain null over time.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The kinetic energies of the molecular Brownian motions, together with those of molecular rotations and vibrations, sum up to the caloric component of a fluid's internal energy (the equipartition theorem).
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This motion is named after the Scottish botanist Robert Brown, who first described the phenomenon in 1827, while looking through a microscope at pollen of the plant *Clarkia pulchella* immersed in water.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In 1900, the French mathematician Louis Bachelier modeled the stochastic process now called Brownian motion in his doctoral thesis, The Theory of Speculation (Théorie de la spéculation), prepared under the supervision of Henri Poincaré.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Then, in 1905, theoretical physicist Albert Einstein published a paper in which he modelled the motion of the pollen particles as being moved by individual water molecules, making one of his first major scientific contributions.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The direction of the force of atomic bombardment is constantly changing, and at different times the particle is hit more on one side than another, leading to the seemingly random nature of the motion.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This explanation of Brownian motion served as convincing evidence that atoms and molecules exist and was further verified experimentally by Jean Perrin in 1908.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Perrin was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926 "for his work on the discontinuous structure of matter".
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The many-body interactions that yield the Brownian pattern cannot be solved by a model accounting for every involved molecule.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Consequently, only probabilistic models applied to molecular populations can be employed to describe it.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Two such models of the statistical mechanics, due to Einstein and Smoluchowski, are presented below.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Another, pure probabilistic class of models is the class of the stochastic process models.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] There exist sequences of both simpler and more complicated stochastic processes which converge (in the limit) to Brownian motion (see random walk and Donsker's theorem).
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The Roman philosopher-poet Lucretius' scientific poem *On the Nature of Things* (c.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] 60 BC) has a remarkable description of the motion of dust particles in verses 113–140 from Book II.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The formal scientific discovery of this phenomenon is credited to the botanist Robert Brown in 1827.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Brown was studying plant reproduction when he observed pollen grains of the plant *Clarkia pulchella* in water under a simple microscope.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] These grains contain minute particles on the order of 1/4,000th of an inch (6.4 microns) in size.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] He observed these particles executing a continuous, jittery motion.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] By repeating the experiment with particles of inorganic matter, such as glass and rock dust, he was able to rule out that the motion was life-related, although its physical origin was yet to be explained.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The mathematics of much of stochastic analysis, including the mathematics of Brownian motion, was introduced by Louis Bachelier in 1900 in his PhD thesis "The theory of speculation", in which he presented an innovative probabilistic analysis of the stock and option markets.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] However, this pioneering mathematical work connecting random walks to continuous time was largely unknown until the 1950s.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The instantaneous velocity of the Brownian motion can be defined as *v* = Δ*x*/Δ*t*, when Δ*t* << *τ*, where τ is the momentum relaxation time.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In this way Einstein was able to determine the size of atoms, and how many atoms there are in a mole, or the molecular weight in grams, of a gas.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In accordance to Avogadro's law, this volume is the same for all ideal gases, namely 22.414 liters at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The first part of Einstein's argument was to determine how far a Brownian particle travels in a given time interval.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Classical mechanics is unable to determine this distance because of the enormous number of bombardments a Brownian particle will undergo, roughly of the order of 1014 collisions per second.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The integral in the first term is equal to one by the definition of probability, and the second and other even terms (i.e. first and other odd moments) vanish because of space symmetry.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The first moment is seen to vanish, meaning that the Brownian particle is equally likely to move to the left as it is to move to the right.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The second moment is, however, non-vanishing, being given by $\mathbb {E} {\left[x^{2}\right]}=2Dt.$ This equation expresses the mean squared displacement in terms of the time elapsed and the diffusivity.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] From this expression Einstein argued that the displacement of a Brownian particle is not proportional to the elapsed time, but rather to its square root.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] His argument is based on a conceptual switch from the "ensemble" of Brownian particles to the "single" Brownian particle: we can speak of the relative number of particles at a single instant just as well as of the time it takes a Brownian particle to reach a given point.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The second part of Einstein's theory relates the diffusion constant to physically measurable quantities, such as the mean squared displacement of a particle in a given time interval.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This result enables the experimental determination of the Avogadro number and therefore the size of molecules.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Einstein analyzed a dynamic equilibrium being established between opposing forces.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The beauty of his argument is that the final result does not depend upon which forces are involved in setting up the dynamic equilibrium.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In his original treatment, Einstein considered an osmotic pressure experiment, but the same conclusion can be reached in other ways.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Consider, for instance, particles suspended in a viscous fluid in a gravitational field.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Gravity tends to make the particles settle, whereas diffusion acts to homogenize them, driving them into regions of smaller concentration.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Under the action of gravity, a particle acquires a downward speed of *v* = *μmg*, where m is the mass of the particle, g is the acceleration due to gravity, and μ is the particle's mobility in the fluid.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] George Stokes had shown that the mobility for a spherical particle with radius r is $\mu ={\tfrac {1}{6\pi \eta r}}$ , where η is the dynamic viscosity of the fluid.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Dynamic equilibrium is established because the more that particles are pulled down by gravity, the greater the tendency for the particles to migrate to regions of lower concentration.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The flux is given by Fick's law, $J=-D{\frac {d\rho }{dh}},$ where *J* = *ρv*.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In a state of dynamical equilibrium, this speed must also be equal to *v* = *μmg*.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Both expressions for v are proportional to *mg*, reflecting that the derivation is independent of the type of forces considered.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Similarly, one can derive an equivalent formula for identical charged particles of charge q in a uniform electric field of magnitude E, where *mg* is replaced with the electrostatic force *qE*.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] By measuring the mean squared displacement over a time interval along with the universal gas constant *R*, the temperature T, the viscosity η, and the particle radius r, the Avogadro constant *N*A can be determined.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The type of dynamical equilibrium proposed by Einstein was not new.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] It had been pointed out previously by J.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] An identical expression to Einstein's formula for the diffusion coefficient was also found by Walther Nernst in 1888 in which he expressed the diffusion coefficient as the ratio of the osmotic pressure to the ratio of the frictional force and the velocity to which it gives rise.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The former was equated to the law of van 't Hoff while the latter was given by Stokes's law.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] He writes $k'=p_{o}/k$ for the diffusion coefficient k′, where $p_{o}$ is the osmotic pressure and k is the ratio of the frictional force to the molecular viscosity which he assumes is given by Stokes's formula for the viscosity.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Introducing the ideal gas law per unit volume for the osmotic pressure, the formula becomes identical to that of Einstein's.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The use of Stokes's law in Nernst's case, as well as in Einstein and Smoluchowski, is not strictly applicable since it does not apply to the case where the radius of the sphere is small in comparison with the mean free path.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Confirming Einstein's formula experimentally proved difficult.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Initial attempts by Theodor Svedberg in 1906 and 1907 were critiqued by Einstein and by Perrin as not measuring a quantity directly comparable to the formula.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Victor Henri in 1908 took cinematographic shots through a microscope and found quantitative disagreement with the formula but again the analysis was uncertain.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Einstein's predictions were finally confirmed in a series of experiments carried out by Chaudesaigues in 1908 and Perrin in 1909.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The confirmation of Einstein's theory constituted empirical progress for the kinetic theory of heat.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In essence, Einstein showed that the motion can be predicted directly from the kinetic model of thermal equilibrium.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The importance of the theory lay in the fact that it confirmed the kinetic theory's account of the second law of thermodynamics as being an essentially statistical law.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Smoluchowski's theory of Brownian motion, later contextualized in comprehensive reviews of stochastic physics, starts from the same premise as that of Einstein and derives the same probability distribution *ρ*(*x*, *t*) for the displacement of a Brownian particle along the x axis in time t.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] He therefore gets the same expression for the mean squared displacement: ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} {\left[(\Delta x)^{2}\right]}}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Associating the kinetic energy ${\textstyle mu^{2}/2}$ with the thermal energy ${\textstyle RT/N}$ , the expression for the mean squared displacement is 64/27 times that found by Einstein.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Smoluchowski attempts to answer the question of why a Brownian particle should be displaced by bombardments of smaller particles when the probabilities for striking it in the forward and rear directions are exactly equal.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] $\mathbb {E} {\left[2m-n\right]}\approx {\sqrt {\frac {n}{2\pi }}}$ showing that the net displacement increases proportionally to the square root of the total population of collision events.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Suppose that a Brownian particle of mass M is surrounded by lighter particles of mass m which are traveling at a speed u.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] These orders of magnitude do not take into consideration the velocity of the Brownian particle, U, which actively depends on the collisions that tend to accelerate and decelerate it.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The larger U is, the greater will be the resistive drag of collisions that will retard it, so that the velocity of a Brownian particle can never increase without limit.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] If such an unbounded process could occur, it would be tantamount to a perpetual motion machine of the second kind.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Since the equipartition of energy applies to this system in thermal equilibrium, the kinetic energy of the Brownian particle, ${\textstyle MU^{2}/2}$ , will be equal, on the average, to the kinetic energy of the surrounding fluid particle, ${\textstyle mu^{2}/2}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In 1906, Smoluchowski published a one-dimensional model to describe a particle undergoing Brownian motion.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The model assumes collisions with ${\textstyle M\gg m}$ where M is the test particle's mass and m the mass of one of the individual particles composing the fluid.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] If ${\textstyle N_{\text{R}}}$ is the number of collisions from the right and ${\textstyle N_{\text{L}}}$ the number of collisions from the left then after N collisions the particle's velocity will have changed by ${\textstyle \Delta V(2N_{\text{R}}-N)}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The multiplicity is then simply given by: ${\binom {N}{N_{\text{R}}}}={\frac {N!}{N_{\text{R}}!(N-N_{\text{R}})!}}$ and the total number of possible states is given by ${\textstyle 2^{N}}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] As a result of its simplicity, Smoluchowski's 1D model can only qualitatively describe Brownian motion.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] For a realistic particle undergoing Brownian motion in a fluid, many of the assumptions do not apply.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] For example, the assumption that on average there are an equal number of collisions from the right as from the left falls apart once the particle is in motion, as it will sweep into particles in its path and create a velocity-dependent drag force.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Furthermore, there would be a continuous statistical distribution of different possible ${\textstyle \Delta V}$ s governed by the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution of fluid molecule velocities, rather than a single discrete value in a physical liquid or gas.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The diffusion equation yields an approximation of the time evolution of the probability density function associated with the position of the particle going under a Brownian movement under the physical definition.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The approximation becomes valid on timescales much larger than the timescale of individual atomic collisions, since it does not include a term to describe the acceleration of particles during collision.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The time evolution of the position of the Brownian particle over all time scales described using the Langevin equation, an equation that involves a random force field representing the effect of the thermal fluctuations of the solvent on the particle.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] At longer times scales, where acceleration is negligible, individual particle dynamics can be approximated using Brownian dynamics in place of Langevin dynamics.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In stellar dynamics, a massive body (star, black hole, etc.) can experience Brownian motion as it responds to gravitational forces from surrounding stars.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The rms velocity V of the massive object, of mass M, is related to the rms velocity $v_{\star }$ of the background stars by $MV^{2}\approx mv_{\star }^{2}$ where $m\ll M$ is the mass of the background stars.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The gravitational force from the massive object causes nearby stars to move faster than they otherwise would, increasing both $v_{\star }$ and V.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The Brownian velocity of Sgr A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way galaxy, is predicted from this formula to be less than 1 km s−1.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In mathematics, Brownian motion is described by the **Wiener process**, a continuous-time stochastic process named in honor of Norbert Wiener.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] It is one of the best known Lévy processes (càdlàg stochastic processes with stationary independent increments) and occurs frequently in pure and applied mathematics, economics and physics.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ denotes the normal distribution with expected value μ and variance *σ*2.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In addition, for some filtration ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ , $W_{t}$ is ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ measurable for all $t\geq 0$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] An alternative characterisation of the Wiener process is the so-called *Lévy characterisation* that says that the Wiener process is an almost surely continuous martingale with *W*0 = 0 and quadratic variation $[W_{t},W_{t}]=t$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] A third characterisation is that the Wiener process has a spectral representation as a sine series whose coefficients are independent ${\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ random variables.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This representation can be obtained using the Kosambi–Karhunen–Loève theorem.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The Wiener process can be constructed as the scaling limit of a random walk, or other discrete-time stochastic processes with stationary independent increments.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Like the random walk, the Wiener process is recurrent in one or two dimensions (meaning that it returns almost surely to any fixed neighborhood of the origin infinitely often) whereas it is not recurrent in dimensions three and higher.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Unlike the random walk, it is scale invariant.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The Brownian motion can be modeled by a random walk.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] In the general case, Brownian motion is a Markov process and described by stochastic integral equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The French mathematician Paul Lévy proved the following theorem, which gives a necessary and sufficient condition for a continuous **R***n*-valued stochastic process *X* to actually be n-dimensional Brownian motion.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Hence, Lévy's condition can actually be used as an alternative definition of Brownian motion.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Let *X* = (*X*1, ..., *X**n*) be a continuous stochastic process on a probability space (Ω, Σ, **P**) taking values in **R***n*.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] 2. for all 1 ≤ *i*, *j* ≤ *n*, *X**i*(*t*) *X**j*(*t*) − *δ**ij* *t* is a martingale with respect to **P** (and its own natural filtration), where *δ**ij* denotes the Kronecker delta.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The spectral content of a stochastic process $X_{t}$ can be found from the power spectral density, formally defined as $S(\omega )=\lim _{T\to \infty }{\frac {1}{T}}\mathbb {E} \left\{\left|\int _{0}^{T}e^{i\omega t}X_{t}dt\right|^{2}\right\},$ where $\mathbb {E}$ stands for the expected value.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The power spectral density of Brownian motion is found to be $S_{BM}(\omega )={\frac {4D}{\omega ^{2}}}.$ where D is the diffusion coefficient of *Xt*.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] For sufficiently long realization times, the expected value of the power spectrum of a single trajectory converges to the formally defined power spectral density $S(\omega )$ , but its coefficient of variation $\gamma =\sigma /\mu$ tends to ${\sqrt {5}}/2$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This implies the distribution of $S^{(1)}(\omega ,T)$ is broad even in the infinite time limit.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Brownian motion is usually considered to take place in Euclidean space.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] It is natural to consider how such motion generalizes to more complex shapes, such as surfaces or higher dimensional manifolds.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The formalization requires the space to possess some form of a derivative, as well as a metric, so that a Laplacian can be defined.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Both of these are available on Riemannian manifolds.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Riemannian manifolds have the property that geodesics can be described in polar coordinates; that is, displacements are always in a radial direction, at some given angle.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Uniform random motion is then described by Gaussians along the radial direction, independent of the angle, the same as in Euclidean space.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The infinitesimal generator (and hence characteristic operator) of Brownian motion on Euclidean **R***n* is ⁠1/2⁠Δ, where Δ denotes the Laplace operator.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] Brownian motion on an m-dimensional Riemannian manifold (*M*, *g*) can be defined as diffusion on M with the characteristic operator given by ⁠1/2⁠ΔLB, half the Laplace–Beltrami operator ΔLB.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] One of the topics of study is a characterization of the Poincaré recurrence time for such systems.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] The narrow escape problem is that of calculating the mean escape time.
[src:stochastic-processes/brownian-motion] This time diverges as the window shrinks, thus rendering the calculation a singular perturbation problem.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] In probability theory and statistics, a **Gaussian process** is a stochastic process (a collection of random variables indexed by time or space), such that every finite collection of those random variables has a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The distribution of a Gaussian process is the joint distribution of all those (infinitely many) random variables, and as such, it is a distribution over functions with a continuous domain, e.g. time or space.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The concept of Gaussian processes is named after Carl Friedrich Gauss because it is based on the notion of the Gaussian distribution (normal distribution).
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can be seen as an infinite-dimensional generalization of multivariate normal distributions.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are useful in statistical modelling, benefiting from properties inherited from the normal distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For example, if a random process is modelled as a Gaussian process, the distributions of various derived quantities can be obtained explicitly.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Such quantities include the average value of the process over a range of times and the error in estimating the average using sample values at a small set of times.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] While exact models often scale poorly as the amount of data increases, multiple approximation methods have been developed which often retain good accuracy while drastically reducing computation time.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] is a multivariate Gaussian random variable.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] As the sum of independent and Gaussian distributed random variables is again Gaussian distributed, that is the same as saying every linear combination of $(X_{t_{1}},\ldots ,X_{t_{k}})$ has a univariate Gaussian (or normal) distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The numbers $\sigma _{\ell j}^{2}$ and $\mu _{\ell }$ can be shown to be the covariances and means of the variables in the process.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For general stochastic processes strict-sense stationarity implies wide-sense stationarity but not every wide-sense stationary stochastic process is strict-sense stationary.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] However, for a Gaussian stochastic process the two concepts are equivalent.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Therefore, stationary Gaussian process is completely determined by its one-parameter mean function and covariance function.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] There is an explicit representation for stationary Gaussian processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] where $\xi _{1}$ and $\xi _{2}$ are independent random variables with the standard normal distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A key fact of Gaussian processes is that they can be completely defined by their second-order statistics.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Thus, if a Gaussian process is assumed to have mean zero, defining the covariance function completely defines the process' behaviour.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Importantly the non-negative definiteness of this function enables its spectral decomposition using the Karhunen–Loève expansion.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Basic aspects that can be defined through the covariance function are the process' stationarity, isotropy, smoothness and periodicity.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Stationarity refers to the process' behaviour regarding the separation of any two points x and $x'$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] If the process is stationary, the covariance function depends only on $x-x'$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For example, the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is stationary.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] If the process depends only on $|x-x'|$ , the Euclidean distance (not the direction) between x and $x'$ , then the process is considered isotropic.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A process that is concurrently stationary and isotropic is considered to be homogeneous; in practice these properties reflect the differences (or rather the lack of them) in the behaviour of the process given the location of the observer.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Ultimately Gaussian processes translate as taking priors on functions and the smoothness of these priors can be induced by the covariance function.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] If we expect that for "near-by" input points x and $x'$ their corresponding output points y and $y'$ to be "near-by" also, then the assumption of continuity is present.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] If we wish to allow for significant displacement then we might choose a rougher covariance function.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Extreme examples of the behaviour is the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck covariance function and the squared exponential where the former is never differentiable and the latter infinitely differentiable.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Periodicity refers to inducing periodic patterns within the behaviour of the process.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Formally, this is achieved by mapping the input x to a two dimensional vector $u(x)=\left(\cos(x),\sin(x)\right)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Here $d=|x-x'|$ , which is a result of the stationary process property, that is, for any stationary process the covariance function will only depend on d .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The parameter $\ell$ is the characteristic length-scale of the process (practically, "how close" two points x and $x'$ have to be to influence each other significantly), *$\delta$* is the Kronecker delta and $\sigma$ the standard deviation of the noise fluctuations.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Moreover, $K_{\nu }$ is the modified Bessel function of order $\nu$ and $\Gamma (\nu )$ is the gamma function evaluated at $\nu$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Importantly, a complicated covariance function can be defined as a linear combination of other simpler covariance functions in order to incorporate different insights about the data-set at hand.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The inferential results are dependent on the values of the hyperparameters $\theta$ (e.g. $\ell$ and $\sigma$ ) defining the model's behaviour.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A popular choice for $\theta$ is to provide *maximum a posteriori* (MAP) estimates of it with some chosen prior.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] If the prior is very near uniform, this is the same as maximizing the marginal likelihood of the process; the marginalization being done over the observed process values y .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] This approach is also known as *maximum likelihood II*, *evidence maximization*, or *empirical Bayes*.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For a Gaussian process, continuity in probability is equivalent to mean-square continuity and continuity with probability one is equivalent to sample continuity.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The latter implies, but is not implied by, continuity in probability.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Continuity in probability holds if and only if the mean and autocovariance are continuous functions.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] In contrast, sample continuity was challenging even for stationary Gaussian processes (as probably noted first by Andrey Kolmogorov), and more challenging for more general processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] As usual, by a sample continuous process one means a process that admits a sample continuous modification.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For a stationary Gaussian process $X=(X_{t})_{t\in \mathbb {R} },$ some conditions on its spectrum are sufficient for sample continuity, but fail to be necessary.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A necessary and sufficient condition, sometimes called Dudley–Fernique theorem, involves the function $\sigma$ defined by $\sigma (h)={\sqrt {{\mathbb {E} }\left[\left(X(t+h)-X(t)\right)^{2}\right]}}$ (the right-hand side does not depend on t due to stationarity).
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Continuity of X in probability is equivalent to continuity of $\sigma$ at $0.$ When convergence of $\sigma (h)$ to 0 (as $h\to 0$ ) is too slow, sample continuity of X may fail.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Sufficiency was announced by Xavier Fernique in 1964, but the first proof was published by Richard M.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] There exist sample continuous processes X such that $I(\sigma )=\infty ;$ they violate condition (*).
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A Wiener process (also known as Brownian motion) is the integral of a white noise generalized Gaussian process.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] It is not stationary, but it has stationary increments.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is a stationary Gaussian process.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The Brownian bridge is (like the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process) an example of a Gaussian process whose increments are not independent.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The fractional Brownian motion is a Gaussian process whose covariance function is a generalisation of that of the Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Let f be a mean-zero Gaussian process $\left\{X_{t};t\in T\right\}$ with a non-negative definite covariance function K and let R be a symmetric and positive semidefinite function.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Then, there exists a Gaussian process X which has the covariance R .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Moreover, the reproducing kernel Hilbert space (RKHS) associated to R coincides with the Cameron–Martin theorem associated space $R(H)$ of X , and all the spaces $R(H)$ , $H_{X}$ , and ${\mathcal {H}}(K)$ are isometric.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] From now on, let ${\mathcal {H}}(R)$ be a reproducing kernel Hilbert space with positive definite kernel R .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] As such, almost all sample paths of a mean-zero Gaussian process with positive definite kernel K will lie outside of the Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}(K)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For many applications of interest some pre-existing knowledge about the system at hand is already given.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A Gaussian process can be used as a prior probability distribution over functions in Bayesian inference.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Given any set of *N* points in the desired domain of the functions, take a multivariate Gaussian whose covariance matrix parameter is the Gram matrix of those *N* points with some desired kernel, and sample from that Gaussian.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] For solution of the multi-output prediction problem, Gaussian process regression for vector-valued function was developed.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] In this method, a 'big' covariance is constructed, which describes the correlations between all the input and output variables taken in *N* points in the desired domain.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] This approach was elaborated in detail for the matrix-valued Gaussian processes and generalised to processes with 'heavier tails' like Student-t processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Inference of continuous values with a Gaussian process prior is known as Gaussian process regression, or kriging; extending Gaussian process regression to multiple target variables is known as *cokriging*.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are thus useful as a powerful non-linear multivariate interpolation tool.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Kriging is also used to extend Gaussian process in the case of mixed integer inputs.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are also commonly used to tackle numerical analysis problems such as numerical integration, solving differential equations, or optimisation in the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can also be used in the context of mixture of experts models, for example.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The underlying rationale of such a learning framework consists in the assumption that a given mapping cannot be well captured by a single Gaussian process model.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Instead, the observation space is divided into subsets, each of which is characterized by a different mapping function; each of these is learned via a different Gaussian process component in the postulated mixture.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Therefore, under the assumption of a zero-mean distribution, ⁠ $f(x')\sim N(0,K(\theta ,x,x'))$ ⁠, where ⁠ $K(\theta ,x,x')$ ⁠ is the covariance matrix between all possible pairs ⁠ $(x,x')$ ⁠ for a given set of hyperparameters *θ*.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] and maximizing this marginal likelihood towards θ provides the complete specification of the Gaussian process *f*.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] One can briefly note at this point that the first term corresponds to a penalty term for a model's failure to fit observed values and the second term to a penalty term that increases proportionally to a model's complexity.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Practically, the posterior mean estimate of ⁠ $f(x^{*})$ ⁠ (the "point estimate") is just a linear combination of the observations ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠; in a similar manner the variance of ⁠ $f(x^{*})$ ⁠ is actually independent of the observations ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] A known bottleneck in Gaussian process prediction is that the computational complexity of inference and likelihood evaluation is cubic in the number of points |*x*|, and as such can become unfeasible for larger data sets.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Works on sparse Gaussian processes, that usually are based on the idea of building a *representative set* for the given process *f*, try to circumvent this issue.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The kriging method can be used in the latent level of a nonlinear mixed-effects model for a spatial functional prediction: this technique is called the latent kriging.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Other classes of scalable Gaussian process for analyzing massive datasets have emerged from the Vecchia approximation and Nearest Neighbor Gaussian Processes (NNGP).
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Examples are the Matérn class covariance functions.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] If this scaling parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ is either known or unknown (i.e. must be marginalized), then the posterior probability, $p(\theta \mid D)$ , i.e. the probability for the hyperparameters $\theta$ given a set of data pairs D of observations of x and $f(x)$ , admits an analytical expression.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Bayesian neural networks are a particular type of Bayesian network that results from treating deep learning and artificial neural network models probabilistically, and assigning a prior distribution to their parameters.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Computation in artificial neural networks is usually organized into sequential layers of artificial neurons.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The number of neurons in a layer is called the layer width.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] As layer width grows large, many Bayesian neural networks reduce to a Gaussian process with a closed form compositional kernel.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] This Gaussian process is called the Neural Network Gaussian Process (NNGP) (not to be confused with the Nearest Neighbor Gaussian Process ).
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] It allows predictions from Bayesian neural networks to be more efficiently evaluated, and provides an analytic tool to understand deep learning models.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes have found increasing applications in many domains of the natural sciences due to their statistical modelling properties.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Molecular property prediction has employed these process models in small molecular datasets due to their inference capabilities and computational costs.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] They are also being increasingly used as surrogate models for force field optimization.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes have also found extensive use in astrophysical and astronomical settings.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can model correlated noise, a specific type of non-Gaussian noise dependent on some underlying unknown distribution correlated with observed values.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] This type of noise is often present in astronomical signals as instrumental systematics or as intrinsic to the observed object as a result of physical processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Correlated noise is often a consideration for exoplanet transit events, and Gaussian processes have been used to de-trend these transit light curves (at timescales greater than that of the transit) to allow detection of weaker, more short-lived signals.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] These processes have also been used to disentangle planetary signals from stellar activity indicators inside radial velocity data, another method of exoplanet detection.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Correlated noise produced by active regions on a star's photosphere (as a result of magnetic field interactions) can be of similar timescales as transit events, and Gaussian process models which handle sparsely sampled data are used to confirm exoplanet detections especially around young stars.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] The variability of rotating, magnetically active Sun-like stars can be modeled fairly accurately using Gaussian processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] This covariance function allows for the limited but feasible determination of stellar periods as a result of parameter $\lambda _{1}$ but lacks physical information about where these active regions are on the star observed.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are also used in the analysis of individual and populations of active galactic nuclei (AGNs) due to their stochastic variability in the optical and radio parts of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Damped random walk kernels in particular have previously been used to identify the extent of broad-line emission regions around supermassive black holes using reverberation mapping, and these kernels can also be used to characterize light curve variations for large AGN populations.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Other astrophysical applications of Gaussian processes include models for pulsar timing and dispersion measure, gravitational wave structure and detector uncertainty (notably in the LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA collaboration), transient classification, and quasi-periodic oscillations.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] In practical applications, Gaussian process models are often evaluated on a grid leading to multivariate normal distributions.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Using these models for prediction or parameter estimation using maximum likelihood requires evaluating a multivariate Gaussian density, which involves calculating the determinant and the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] Both of these operations have cubic computational complexity which means that even for grids of modest sizes, both operations can have a prohibitive computational cost.
[src:stochastic-processes/gaussian-process] This drawback led to the development of multiple approximation methods.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The central concept is the Itô stochastic integral, a stochastic generalization of the Riemann–Stieltjes integral in analysis.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The integrands and the integrators are now stochastic processes: $Y_{t}=\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dX_{s},$ where *H* is a locally square-integrable process adapted to the filtration generated by *X* (Revuz & Yor 1999, Chapter IV), which is a Brownian motion or, more generally, a semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The result of the integration is then another stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Concretely, the integral from 0 to any particular t is a random variable, defined as a limit of a certain sequence of random variables.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The paths of Brownian motion fail to satisfy the requirements to be able to apply the standard techniques of calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] So with the integrand a stochastic process, the Itô stochastic integral amounts to an integral with respect to a function which is not differentiable at any point and has infinite variation over every time interval.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The main insight is that the integral can be defined as long as the integrand *H* is adapted, which loosely speaking means that its value at time t can only depend on information available up until this time.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Roughly speaking, one chooses a sequence of partitions of the interval from 0 to t and constructs Riemann sums.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Every time we are computing a Riemann sum, we are using a particular instantiation of the integrator.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] It is crucial which point in each of the small intervals is used to compute the value of the function.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The limit then is taken in probability as the mesh of the partition is going to zero.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Numerous technical details have to be taken care of to show that this limit exists and is independent of the particular sequence of partitions.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Typically, the left end of the interval is used.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Important results of Itô calculus include the integration by parts formula and Itô's lemma, which is a change of variables formula.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] These differ from the formulas of standard calculus, due to quadratic variation terms.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This can be contrasted to the Stratonovich integral as an alternative formulation; it does follow the chain rule, and does not require Itô's lemma.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The two integral forms can be converted to one-another.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The Stratonovich integral is obtained as the limiting form of a Riemann sum that employs the average of stochastic variable over each small timestep, whereas the Itô integral considers it only at the beginning.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] In mathematical finance, the described evaluation strategy of the integral is conceptualized as that we are first deciding what to do, then observing the change in the prices.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The integrand is how much stock we hold, the integrator represents the movement of the prices, and the integral is how much money we have in total including what our stock is worth, at any given moment.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The prices of stocks and other traded financial assets can be modeled by stochastic processes such as Brownian motion or, more often, geometric Brownian motion (see Black–Scholes).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Then, the Itô stochastic integral represents the payoff of a continuous-time trading strategy consisting of holding an amount *Ht* of the stock at time *t*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] In this situation, the condition that *H* is adapted corresponds to the necessary restriction that the trading strategy can only make use of the available information at any time.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This prevents the possibility of unlimited gains through clairvoyance: buying the stock just before each uptick in the market and selling before each downtick.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Similarly, the condition that *H* is adapted implies that the stochastic integral will not diverge when calculated as a limit of Riemann sums (Revuz & Yor 1999, Chapter IV).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The process *Y* defined before as $Y_{t}=\int _{0}^{t}H\,dX\equiv \int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dX_{s},$ is itself a stochastic process with time parameter *t*, which is also sometimes written as *Y* = *H* · *X* (Rogers & Williams 2000).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Alternatively, the integral is often written in differential form *dY* = *H* *dX*, which is equivalent to *Y* − *Y*0 = *H* · *X*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] A Brownian motion *B* is understood to be an ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ -Brownian motion, which is just a standard Brownian motion with the properties that *B**t* is ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ -measurable and that *B**t*+*s* − *B**t* is independent of ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ for all *s*,*t* ≥ 0 (Revuz & Yor 1999).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The Itô integral can be defined in a manner similar to the Riemann–Stieltjes integral, that is as a limit in probability of Riemann sums; such a limit does not necessarily exist pathwise.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Suppose that *B* is a Wiener process (Brownian motion) and that *H* is a right-continuous (càdlàg), adapted and locally bounded process.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] It can be shown that this limit converges in probability.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For some applications, such as martingale representation theorems and local times, the integral is needed for processes that are not continuous.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The predictable processes form the smallest class that is closed under taking limits of sequences and contains all adapted left-continuous processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] If *H* is any predictable process such that ∫0*t* *H*2 *ds* < ∞ for every *t* ≥ 0 then the integral of *H* with respect to *B* can be defined, and *H* is said to be *B*-integrable.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Any such process can be approximated by a sequence *Hn* of left-continuous, adapted and locally bounded processes, in the sense that $\int _{0}^{t}(H-H_{n})^{2}\,ds\to 0$ in probability.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Then, the Itô integral is $\int _{0}^{t}H\,dB=\lim _{n\to \infty }\int _{0}^{t}H_{n}\,dB$ where, again, the limit can be shown to converge in probability.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The stochastic integral satisfies the Itô isometry $\mathbb {E} \left[\left(\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dB_{s}\right)^{2}\right]=\mathbb {E} \left[\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}^{2}\,ds\right]$ which holds when *H* is bounded or, more generally, when the integral on the right hand side is finite.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Here, *B* is a Brownian motion and it is required that σ is a predictable *B*-integrable process, and μ is predictable and (Lebesgue) integrable.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This is defined for all locally bounded and predictable integrands.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] More generally, it is required that *Hσ* be *B*-integrable and *Hμ* be Lebesgue integrable, so that $\int _{0}^{t}\left(H^{2}\sigma ^{2}+|H\mu |\right)ds<\infty .$ Such predictable processes *H* are called *X*-integrable.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] An important result for the study of Itô processes is Itô's lemma.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This is the stochastic calculus version of the change of variables formula and chain rule.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] It differs from the standard result due to the additional term involving the second derivative of *f*, which comes from the property that Brownian motion has non-zero quadratic variation.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The Itô integral is defined with respect to a semimartingale *X*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] These are processes which can be decomposed as *X* = *M* + *A* for a local martingale *M* and finite variation process *A*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Important examples of such processes include Brownian motion, which is a martingale, and Lévy processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For a left continuous, locally bounded and adapted process *H* the integral *H* · *X* exists, and can be calculated as a limit of Riemann sums.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The stochastic integral of left-continuous processes is general enough for studying much of stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For example, it is sufficient for applications of Itô's Lemma, changes of measure via Girsanov's theorem, and for the study of stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] However, it is inadequate for other important topics such as martingale representation theorems and local times.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The integral extends to all predictable and locally bounded integrands, in a unique way, such that the dominated convergence theorem holds.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The uniqueness of the extension from left-continuous to predictable integrands is a result of the monotone class lemma.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] In general, the stochastic integral *H* · *X* can be defined even in cases where the predictable process *H* is not locally bounded.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Associativity of stochastic integration implies that *H* is *X*-integrable, with integral *H* · *X* = *Y*, if and only if *Y*0 = 0 and *K* · *Y* = (*KH*) · *X*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The set of *X*-integrable processes is denoted by *L*(*X*).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] As with ordinary calculus, integration by parts is an important result in stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The integration by parts formula for the Itô integral differs from the standard result due to the inclusion of a quadratic covariation term.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This term comes from the fact that Itô calculus deals with processes with non-zero quadratic variation, which only occurs for infinite variation processes (such as Brownian motion).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The result is similar to the integration by parts theorem for the Riemann–Stieltjes integral but has an additional quadratic variation term.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Itô's lemma is the version of the chain rule or change of variables formula which applies to the Itô integral.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] It is one of the most powerful and frequently used theorems in stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The formula can be generalized to include an explicit time-dependence in $f,$ and in other ways (see Itô's lemma).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] An important property of the Itô integral is that it preserves the local martingale property.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] If *M* is a local martingale and *H* is a locally bounded predictable process then *H* · *M* is also a local martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For integrands which are not locally bounded, there are examples where *H* · *M* is not a local martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] However, this can only occur when *M* is not continuous.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] If *M* is a continuous local martingale then a predictable process *H* is *M*-integrable if and only if $\int _{0}^{t}H^{2}\,d[M]<\infty ,$ for each t, and *H* · *M* is always a local martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The most general statement for a discontinuous local martingale *M* is that if (*H*2 · [*M*])1/2 is locally integrable then *H* · *M* exists and is a local martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For bounded integrands, the Itô stochastic integral preserves the space of *square integrable* martingales, which is the set of càdlàg martingales *M* such that E[*M**t*2] is finite for all t.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The Itô isometry is often used as an important step in the construction of the stochastic integral, by defining *H* · *M* to be the unique extension of this isometry from a certain class of simple integrands to all bounded and predictable processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For any *p* > 1, and bounded predictable integrand, the stochastic integral preserves the space of *p*-integrable martingales.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] These are càdlàg martingales such that E(|*Mt*|*p*) is finite for all t.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] However, this is not always true in the case where *p* = 1.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] There are examples of integrals of bounded predictable processes with respect to martingales which are not themselves martingales.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The maximum process of a càdlàg process *M* is written as *M*t* = sup*s* ≤*t* |*Ms*|.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For any *p* ≥ 1 and bounded predictable integrand, the stochastic integral preserves the space of càdlàg martingales *M* such that E[(*M*t*)*p*] is finite for all t.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] If *p* > 1 then this is the same as the space of *p*-integrable martingales, by Doob's inequalities.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] These are used to show that if (*M*t*)*p* is integrable and *H* is a bounded predictable process then $\mathbb {E} \left[((H\cdot M)_{t}^{*})^{p}\right]\leq C\mathbb {E} \left[(H^{2}\cdot [M]_{t})^{\frac {p}{2}}\right]<\infty$ and, consequently, *H* · *M* is a *p*-integrable martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] More generally, this statement is true whenever (*H*2 · [*M*])*p*/2 is integrable.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Proofs that the Itô integral is well defined typically proceed by first looking at very simple integrands, such as piecewise constant, left continuous and adapted processes where the integral can be written explicitly.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] It can then be extended to all *B*-integrable processes by localization.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This method allows the integral to be defined with respect to any Itô process.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For a general semimartingale *X*, the decomposition *X* = *M* + *A* into a local martingale *M* plus a finite variation process *A* can be used.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Then, the integral can be shown to exist separately with respect to *M* and *A* and combined using linearity, *H* · *X* = *H* · *M* + *H* · *A*, to get the integral with respect to *X*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The standard Lebesgue–Stieltjes integral allows integration to be defined with respect to finite variation processes, so the existence of the Itô integral for semimartingales will follow from any construction for local martingales.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For a càdlàg square integrable martingale *M*, a generalized form of the Itô isometry can be used.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] First, the Doob–Meyer decomposition theorem is used to show that a decomposition *M*2 = *N* + ⟨*M*⟩ exists, where *N* is a martingale and ⟨*M*⟩ is a right-continuous, increasing and predictable process starting at zero.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This uniquely defines ⟨*M*⟩, which is referred to as the *predictable quadratic variation* of *M*.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The Itô isometry for square integrable martingales is then $\mathbb {E} \left[(H\cdot M_{t})^{2}\right]=\mathbb {E} \left[\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}^{2}\,d\langle M\rangle _{s}\right],$ which can be proved directly for simple predictable integrands.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] As with the case above for Brownian motion, a continuous linear extension can be used to uniquely extend to all predictable integrands satisfying *E*[*H*2 · ⟨*M*⟩*t*] < ∞.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This method can be extended to all local square integrable martingales by localization.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Finally, the Doob–Meyer decomposition can be used to decompose any local martingale into the sum of a local square integrable martingale and a finite variation process, allowing the Itô integral to be constructed with respect to any semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The latter applies directly to local martingales without having to first deal with the square integrable martingale case.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Alternative proofs exist only making use of the fact that *X* is càdlàg, adapted, and the set {*H* · *Xt*: |*H*| ≤ 1 is simple previsible} is bounded in probability for each time *t*, which is an alternative definition for *X* to be a semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] A continuous linear extension can be used to construct the integral for all left-continuous and adapted integrands with right limits everywhere (caglad or L-processes).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This is general enough to be able to apply techniques such as Itô's lemma (Protter 2004).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Also, a Khintchine inequality can be used to prove the dominated convergence theorem and extend the integral to general predictable integrands (Bichteler 2002).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] The Itô calculus is first and foremost defined as an integral calculus as outlined above.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Malliavin calculus provides a theory of differentiation for random variables defined over Wiener space, including an integration by parts formula (Nualart 2006).
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] This representation theorem can be interpreted formally as saying that α is the "time derivative" of *M* with respect to Brownian motion *B*, since α is precisely the process that must be integrated up to time t to obtain *M**t* − *M*0, as in deterministic calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] In physics, usually stochastic differential equations (SDEs), such as Langevin equations, are used, rather than stochastic integrals.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] Here an Itô stochastic differential equation (SDE) is often formulated via ${\dot {x}}_{k}=h_{k}+g_{kl}\xi _{l},$ where $\xi _{j}$ is Gaussian white noise with $\langle \xi _{k}(t_{1})\,\xi _{l}(t_{2})\rangle =\delta _{kl}\delta (t_{1}-t_{2})$ and Einstein's summation convention is used.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] SDEs frequently occur in physics in Stratonovich form, as limits of stochastic differential equations driven by colored noise if the correlation time of the noise term approaches zero.
[src:stochastic-processes/itô-calculus] For a recent treatment of different interpretations of stochastic differential equations see for example (Lau & Lubensky 2007).
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] In probability theory, a **martingale** is a stochastic process in which the expected value of the next observation, given all prior observations, is equal to the most recent value.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] In other words, the conditional expectation of the next value, given the past, is equal to the present value.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] Martingales are used to model fair games, where future expected winnings are equal to the current amount regardless of past outcomes.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] Originally, *martingale* referred to a class of betting strategies that was popular in 18th-century France.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] That is, the conditional expected value of the next observation, given all the past observations, is equal to the most recent observation.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] This expresses the property that the conditional expectation of an observation at time t , given all the observations up to time s , is equal to the observation at time s (provided that $s\leq t$ ).
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] The second property implies that $Y_{n}$ is measurable with respect to $X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] This is also called the martingale property.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] The property of being a martingale involves both the filtration *and* the probability measure (with respect to which the expectations are taken).
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] It is possible that Y could be a martingale with respect to one measure but not another one; the Girsanov theorem offers a way to find a measure with respect to which an Itō process is a martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] In the Banach space setting the conditional expectation is also denoted in operator notation as $\mathbf {E} ^{\Sigma _{s}}Y_{t}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] with "+" in case of "heads" and "−" in case of "tails".
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] There are two generalizations of a martingale that include cases when the current observation $X_{n}$ is not necessarily equal to the future conditional expectation, but instead acts as an upper or lower bound on the conditional expectation.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] A stopping time with respect to a sequence of random variables $X_{1},X_{2},X_{3},\dots$ is a random variable $\tau$ with the property that for each t , the occurrence or non-occurrence of the event $\tau =t$ depends only on the values of $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{t}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] The intuition behind the definition is that at any particular time t , you can look at the sequence so far and tell if it is time to stop.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] An example might be the time at which a gambler leaves the gambling table, which might depend on previous winnings, but not on games that haven't been played yet.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] In some contexts the concept of *stopping time* is defined by requiring only that the occurrence or non-occurrence of the event $\tau =t$ is probabilistically independent of $X_{t+1},X_{t+2},\dots$ but not completely determined by the history up to time t .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] One of the basic properties of martingales is that, if $(X_{t})_{t>0}$ is a (sub-/super-) martingale and $\tau$ is a stopping time, then the corresponding stopped process $(X_{t}^{\tau })_{t>0}$ defined by $X_{t}^{\tau }:=X_{\min\{\tau ,t\}}$ is also a (sub-/super-) martingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] The concept of a stopped martingale leads to a series of important theorems, including the optional stopping theorem which states that, under certain conditions, the expected value of a martingale at a stopping time is equal to its initial value.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] The martingale problem is a framework in stochastic analysis for characterizing solutions to stochastic differential equations (SDEs) through martingale conditions.
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] Let E be a Polish space with Borel $\sigma$ -algebra ${\mathcal {E}}$ , and let ${\mathcal {P}}(E)$ be the set of probability measures on E .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] Suppose $A:{\mathcal {D}}(A)\to C(E)$ is a Markov pregenerator, where ${\mathcal {D}}(A)$ is a dense subspace of $C(E)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] If $\mu =\delta _{\eta }$ (the Dirac measure at $\eta$ ), then $\mathbb {P}$ is said to solve the martingale problem for A with initial point $\eta$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] Solutions to $M(a,b)$ correspond (in a weak sense) to solutions of the SDE $dX_{t}=b(X_{t})\,dt+\sigma (X_{t})\,dB_{t}$ , where $\sigma \sigma ^{\top }=a$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] One sees this by applying the generator A to simple functions such as $x_{i}$ or $x_{i}x_{j}$ , thereby recovering the drift b and the diffusion matrix a .
[src:stochastic-processes/martingale-probability-theory] Martingales form the foundational mathematics behind modern quantitative finance and asset pricing theory.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The process's name derives from the fact that the number of points in any given finite region follows a Poisson distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The process and the distribution are named after French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The process itself was discovered independently and repeatedly in several settings, including experiments on radioactive decay, telephone call arrivals and actuarial science.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This point process is used as a mathematical model for seemingly random processes in numerous disciplines including astronomy, biology, ecology, geology, seismology, physics, economics, image processing, and telecommunications.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The Poisson point process is often defined on the real number line, where it can be viewed as a stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It is used, for example, in queueing theory to model random events distributed in time, such as the arrival of customers at a store, phone calls at an telephone exchange, or the occurrence of earthquakes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, the point process—also known as a **spatial Poisson process**—can represent the locations of scattered objects such as transmitters in a wireless network, particles colliding into a particle detector, or trees in a forest.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The process is widely used in mathematical models and in related fields, including spatial point processes, stochastic geometry, spatial statistics and continuum percolation theory.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The point process depends on a single mathematical object, which, depending on the context, may be a constant, a locally integrable function or, in more general settings, a Radon measure.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the first case, the constant, known as the **rate** or **intensity**, is the average density of the points in the Poisson process located in some region of space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The resulting point process is called a **homogeneous** or **stationary Poisson point process**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the second case, the point process is called an **inhomogeneous** or **nonhomogeneous** **Poisson point process**, and the average density of points depend on the location of the underlying space of the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The word *point* is often omitted, but there are other *Poisson processes* of objects, which, instead of points, consist of more complicated mathematical objects such as lines and polygons, and such processes can be based on the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Both the homogeneous and nonhomogeneous Poisson point processes are particular cases of the generalized renewal process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Depending on the setting, the process has several equivalent definitions as well as definitions of varying generality owing to its many applications and characterizations.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Consequently, the notation, terminology and level of mathematical rigour used to define and study the Poisson point process and points processes in general vary according to the context.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Despite all this, the Poisson point process has two key properties—the Poisson property and the independence property— that play an essential role in all settings where the Poisson point process is used.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The two properties are not logically independent; indeed, the Poisson distribution of point counts implies the independence property, while in the converse direction the assumptions that: (i) the point process is simple, (ii) has no fixed atoms, and (iii) is a.s. boundedly finite are required.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] A Poisson point process is characterized via the Poisson distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle n!}$ denotes factorial and the parameter ${\textstyle \Lambda }$ determines the shape of the distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] By definition, a Poisson point process has the property that the number of points in a bounded region of the process's underlying space is a Poisson-distributed random variable.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Consider a collection of disjoint and bounded subregions of the underlying space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] By definition, the number of points of a Poisson point process in each bounded subregion will be completely independent of all the others.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This property is known under several names such as *complete randomness*, *complete independence*, or *independent scattering* and is common to all Poisson point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, there is a lack of interaction between different regions and the points in general, which motivates the Poisson process being sometimes called a *purely* or *completely* random process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The parameter, called **rate** or **intensity**, is related to the expected (or average) number of Poisson points existing in some bounded region, where *rate* is usually used when the underlying space has one dimension.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ can be interpreted as the average number of points per some unit of extent such as length, area, volume, or time, depending on the underlying mathematical space, and it is also called the *mean density* or *mean rate*; see Terminology.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The homogeneous Poisson point process, when considered on the positive half-line, can be defined as a counting process, a type of stochastic process, which can be denoted as ${\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] A counting process represents the total number of occurrences or events that have happened up to and including time ${\textstyle t}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The Poisson counting process can also be defined by stating that the time differences between events of the counting process are exponential variables with mean ${\textstyle 1/\lambda }$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The time differences between the events or arrivals are known as **interarrival** or **interoccurrence** times.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Interpreted as a point process, a Poisson point process can be defined on the real line by considering the number of points of the process in the interval ${\textstyle (a,b]}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, ${\textstyle N(a,b]}$ is a Poisson random variable with mean ${\textstyle \lambda (b-a)}$ , where ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the number of points in any two disjoint intervals, say, ${\textstyle (a_{1},b_{1}]}$ and ${\textstyle (a_{2},b_{2}]}$ are independent of each other, and this extends to any finite number of disjoint intervals.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the queueing theory context, one can consider a point existing (in an interval) as an *event*, but this is different to the word event in the probability theory sense.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It follows that ${\textstyle \lambda }$ is the expected number of *arrivals* that occur per unit of time.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, for any finite ${\textstyle t>0}$ , the random variable ${\textstyle N(a+t,b+t]}$ is independent of ${\textstyle t}$ , so it is also called a stationary Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\operatorname {E}$ denotes the expectation operator.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, the parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ of the Poisson process coincides with the *density* of points.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the homogeneous Poisson point process adheres to its own form of the (strong) law of large numbers.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle \lim }$ denotes the limit of a function, and $\lambda$ is expected number of arrivals occurred per unit of time.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The distance between two consecutive points of a point process on the real line will be an exponential random variable with parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ (or equivalently, mean ${\textstyle 1/\lambda }$ ).
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] A point process is called a **simple point process** when the probability of any of its two points coinciding in the same position, on the underlying space, is zero.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For point processes in general on the real line, the property of orderliness implies that the process is simple, which is the case for the homogeneous Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] On the real line, the Poisson process is a type of continuous-time Markov process known as a birth process, a special case of the birth–death process (with just births and zero deaths).
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] More complicated processes with the Markov property, such as Markov arrival processes, have been defined where the Poisson process is a special case.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If the homogeneous Poisson process is considered just on the half-line ${\textstyle [0,\infty )}$ , which can be the case when ${\textstyle t}$ represents time then the resulting process is not truly invariant under translation.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In that case the Poisson process is no longer stationary, according to some definitions of stationarity.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] There have been many applications of the homogeneous Poisson process on the real line in an attempt to model seemingly random and independent events occurring.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It has a fundamental role in queueing theory, which is the probability field of developing suitable stochastic models to represent the random arrival and departure of certain phenomena.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, customers arriving and being served or phone calls arriving at a phone exchange can be both studied with techniques from queueing theory.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The homogeneous Poisson process on the real line is considered one of the simplest stochastic processes for counting random numbers of points.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This process can be generalized in a number of ways.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] One possible generalization is to extend the distribution of interarrival times from the exponential distribution to other distributions, which introduces the stochastic process known as a renewal process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Another generalization is to define the Poisson point process on higher dimensional spaces such as the plane.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] A **spatial Poisson process** is a Poisson point process defined in the plane $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For its mathematical definition, one first considers a bounded, open or closed (or more precisely, Borel measurable) region ${\textstyle B}$ of the plane.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points of a point process $\textstyle N$ existing in this region $\textstyle B\subset \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is a random variable, denoted by $\textstyle N(B)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ denotes the area of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For some finite integer $\textstyle k\geq 1$ , we can give the finite-dimensional distribution of the homogeneous Poisson point process by first considering a collection of disjoint, bounded Borel (measurable) sets $\textstyle B_{1},\dots ,B_{k}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points of the point process $\textstyle N$ existing in $\textstyle B_{i}$ can be written as $\textstyle N(B_{i})$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The spatial Poisson point process features prominently in spatial statistics, stochastic geometry, and continuum percolation theory.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This point process is applied in various physical sciences such as a model developed for alpha particles being detected.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In recent years, it has been frequently used to model seemingly disordered spatial configurations of certain wireless communication networks.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, models for cellular or mobile phone networks have been developed where it is assumed the phone network transmitters, known as base stations, are positioned according to a homogeneous Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The previous homogeneous Poisson point process immediately extends to higher dimensions by replacing the notion of area with (high dimensional) volume.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ now denotes the $\textstyle d$ -dimensional volume of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, for a collection of disjoint, bounded Borel sets $\textstyle B_{1},\dots ,B_{k}\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , let $\textstyle N(B_{i})$ denote the number of points of $\textstyle N$ existing in $\textstyle B_{i}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Homogeneous Poisson point processes do not depend on the position of the underlying space through its parameter $\textstyle \lambda$ , which implies it is both a stationary process (invariant to translation) and an isotropic (invariant to rotation) stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Similarly to the one-dimensional case, the homogeneous point process is restricted to some bounded subset of ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}}$ , then depending on some definitions of stationarity, the process is no longer stationary.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If the homogeneous point process is defined on the real line as a mathematical model for occurrences of some phenomenon, then it has the characteristic that the positions of these occurrences or events on the real line (often interpreted as time) will be uniformly distributed.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] More specifically, if an event occurs (according to this process) in an interval $\textstyle (a,b]$ where $\textstyle a\leq b$ , then its location will be a uniform random variable defined on that interval.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the homogeneous point process is sometimes called the *uniform* Poisson point process (see Terminology).
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This uniformity property extends to higher dimensions in the Cartesian coordinate, but not in, for example, polar coordinates.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The **inhomogeneous** or **nonhomogeneous** **Poisson point process** (see Terminology) is a Poisson point process with a Poisson parameter set as some location-dependent function in the underlying space on which the Poisson process is defined.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] On the real line, the inhomogeneous or non-homogeneous Poisson point process has mean measure given by a one-dimensional integral.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For two real numbers $\textstyle a$ and $\textstyle b$ , where $\textstyle a\leq b$ , denote by $\textstyle N(a,b]$ the number points of an inhomogeneous Poisson process with intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (t)$ occurring in the interval $\textstyle (a,b]$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] which means that the random variable $\textstyle N(a,b]$ is a Poisson random variable with mean $\textstyle \operatorname {E} [N(a,b]]=\Lambda (a,b)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] A feature of the one-dimension setting, is that an inhomogeneous Poisson process can be transformed into a homogeneous by a monotone transformation or mapping, which is achieved with the inverse of $\textstyle \Lambda$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The inhomogeneous Poisson point process, when considered on the positive half-line, is also sometimes defined as a counting process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] With this interpretation, the process, which is sometimes written as $\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}$ , represents the total number of occurrences or events that have happened up to and including time $\textstyle t$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle o(h)$ is asymptotic or little-o notation for $\textstyle o(h)/h\rightarrow 0$ as $\textstyle h\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the case of point processes with refractoriness (e.g., neural spike trains) a stronger version of property 4 applies: $\Pr\{N(t+h)-N(t)\geq 2\}=o(h^{2})$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] An inhomogeneous Poisson process defined in the plane $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is called a **spatial Poisson process** It is defined with intensity function and its intensity measure is obtained performing a surface integral of its intensity function over some region.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle B}$ is some bounded region in the plane ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, ${\textstyle \Lambda (B)}$ corresponds to a surface integral while in ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}}$ the integral becomes a ( ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional) volume integral.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] When the real line is interpreted as time, the inhomogeneous process is used in the fields of counting processes and in queueing theory.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, the Poisson point process is important in the related disciplines of stochastic geometry and spatial statistics.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The intensity measure of this point process is dependent on the location of underlying space, which means it can be used to model phenomena with a density that varies over some region.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, the phenomena can be represented as points that have a location-dependent density.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This processes has been used in various disciplines and uses include the study of salmon and sea lice in the oceans, forestry, and search problems.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, given a homogeneous Poisson point process on the real line, the probability of finding a single point of the process in a small interval of width ${\textstyle \delta }$ is approximately ${\textstyle \lambda \delta }$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In fact, such intuition is how the Poisson point process is sometimes introduced and its distribution derived.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If a Poisson point process has an intensity measure that is a locally finite and diffuse (or non-atomic), then it is a **simple point process**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For a simple point process, the probability of a point existing at a single point or location in the underlying (state) space is either zero or one.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This implies that, with probability one, no two (or more) points of a Poisson point process coincide in location in the underlying space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Simulating a Poisson point process on a computer is usually done in a bounded region of space, known as a simulation *window*, and requires two steps: appropriately creating a random number of points and then suitably placing the points in a random manner.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Both these two steps depend on the specific Poisson point process that is being simulated.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points ${\textstyle N}$ in the window, denoted here by ${\textstyle W}$ , needs to be simulated, which is done by using a (pseudo)-random number generating function capable of simulating Poisson random variables.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous case with the constant ${\textstyle \lambda }$ , the mean of the Poisson random variable ${\textstyle N}$ is set to ${\textstyle \lambda |W|}$ where ${\textstyle |W|}$ is the length, area or ( ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional) volume of ${\textstyle W}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The second stage requires randomly placing the $\textstyle N$ points in the window $\textstyle W$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous case in one dimension, all points are uniformly and independently placed in the window or interval $\textstyle W$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For higher dimensions in a Cartesian coordinate system, each coordinate is uniformly and independently placed in the window $\textstyle W$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If the window is not a subspace of Cartesian space (for example, inside a unit sphere or on the surface of a unit sphere), then the points will not be uniformly placed in $\textstyle W$ , and suitable change of coordinates (from Cartesian) are needed.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For the inhomogeneous case, a couple of different methods can be used depending on the nature of the intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If the intensity function is sufficiently simple, then independent and random non-uniform (Cartesian or other) coordinates of the points can be generated.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For more complicated intensity functions, one can use an acceptance-rejection method, which consists of using (or 'accepting') only certain random points and not using (or 'rejecting') the other points, based on the ratio:.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle x_{i}$ is the point under consideration for acceptance or rejection.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In measure theory, the Poisson point process can be further generalized to what is sometimes known as the **general Poisson point process** or **general Poisson process** by using a Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ , which is a locally finite measure.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In general, this Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ can be atomic, which means multiple points of the Poisson point process can exist in the same location of the underlying space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In this situation, the number of points at $\textstyle x$ is a Poisson random variable with mean $\textstyle \Lambda ({x})$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] But sometimes the converse is assumed, so the Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ is diffuse or non-atomic.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where the density $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ is known, among other terms, as the intensity function.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Despite its name, the Poisson point process was neither discovered nor studied by its namesake.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It is cited as an example of Stigler's law of eponymy.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The name arises from the process's inherent relation to the Poisson distribution, derived by Poisson as a limiting case of the binomial distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It describes the probability of the sum of $\textstyle n$ Bernoulli trials with probability $\textstyle p$ , often likened to the number of heads (or tails) after $\textstyle n$ biased coin flips with the probability of a head (or tail) occurring being $\textstyle p$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For some positive constant $\textstyle \Lambda >0$ , as $\textstyle n$ increases towards infinity and $\textstyle p$ decreases towards zero such that the product $\textstyle np=\Lambda$ is fixed, the Poisson distribution more closely approximates that of the binomial.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In 1841, Poisson derived the Poisson distribution by studying the binomial distribution in the limit as $\textstyle p$ goes to zero and $\textstyle n$ goes to infinity.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The distribution appears only once in Poisson's work, and the result was not well known during his time.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Over the following years, others used the distribution without citing Poisson, including Philipp Ludwig von Seidel and Ernst Abbe.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] At the end of the 19th century, Ladislaus Bortkiewicz revived interest in the distribution by citing Poisson and using real data on the number of deaths from horse kicks in the Prussian army.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] There are a number of claims for early uses or discoveries of the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] This work inspired Simon Newcomb to study the problem and to calculate the Poisson distribution as an approximation for the binomial distribution in 1860.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] At the beginning of the 20th century the Poisson process (in one dimension) would arise independently in different situations.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In Sweden 1903, Filip Lundberg published a thesis containing work, now considered fundamental and pioneering, where he proposed to model insurance claims with a homogeneous Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Erlang derived the Poisson distribution in 1909 when developing a mathematical model for the number of incoming phone calls in a finite time interval.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Erlang unaware of Poisson's earlier work and assumed that the number phone calls arriving in each interval of time were independent of each other.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] He then found the limiting case, which is effectively recasting the Poisson distribution as a limit of the binomial distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In 1910 Ernest Rutherford and Hans Geiger published experimental results on counting alpha particles.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Their experimental work had mathematical contributions from Harry Bateman, who derived Poisson probabilities as a solution to a family of differential equations, though the solution had been derived earlier, resulting in the independent discovery of the Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] After this time, there were many studies and applications of the Poisson process, but its early history is complicated, which has been explained by the various applications of the process in numerous fields by biologists, ecologists, engineers and various physical scientists.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The early results were published in different languages and in different settings, with no standard terminology and notation used.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, in 1922 Swedish chemist and Nobel Laureate Theodor Svedberg proposed a model in which a spatial Poisson point process is the underlying process to study how plants are distributed in plant communities.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] A number of mathematicians started studying the process in the early 1930s, and important contributions were made by Andrey Kolmogorov, William Feller and Aleksandr Khinchin, among others.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the field of teletraffic engineering, mathematicians and statisticians studied and used Poisson and other point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The Swede Conny Palm in his 1943 dissertation studied the Poisson and other point processes in the one-dimensional setting by examining them in terms of the statistical or stochastic dependence between the points in time.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In his work exists the first known recorded use of the term *point processes* as *Punktprozesse* in German.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It is believed that William Feller was the first in print to refer to it as the *Poisson process* in a 1940 paper.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Although the Swede Ove Lundberg used the term *Poisson process* in his 1940 PhD dissertation, in which Feller was acknowledged as an influence, it has been claimed that Feller coined the term before 1940.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It has been remarked that both Feller and Lundberg used the term as though it were well-known, implying it was already in spoken use by then.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The terminology of point process theory in general has been criticized for being too varied.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In addition to the word *point* often being omitted, the homogeneous Poisson (point) process is also called a *stationary* Poisson (point) process, as well as *uniform* Poisson (point) process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The inhomogeneous Poisson point process, as well as being called *nonhomogeneous*, is also referred to as the *non-stationary* Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The term *point process* has been criticized, as the term *process* can suggest over time and space, so *random point field*, resulting in the terms *Poisson random point field* or *Poisson point field* being also used.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The underlying mathematical space of the Poisson point process is called a **carrier space**, or **state space**, though the latter term has a different meaning in the context of stochastic processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the context of point processes, the term "state space" can mean the space on which the point process is defined such as the real line, which corresponds to the index set or parameter set in stochastic process terminology.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ is called the *intensity measure*, *mean measure*, or *parameter measure*, as there are no standard terms.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If $\textstyle \Lambda$ has a derivative or density, denoted by $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ , is called the *intensity function* of the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous Poisson point process, the derivative of the intensity measure is simply a constant $\textstyle \lambda >0$ , which can be referred to as the *rate*, usually when the underlying space is the real line, or the *intensity*.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] It is also called the *mean rate* or the *mean density* or *rate*.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For $\textstyle \lambda =1$ , the corresponding process is sometimes referred to as the *standard Poisson* (point) process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The extent of the Poisson point process is sometimes called the *exposure*.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The notation of the Poisson point process depends on its setting and the field it is being applied in.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, on the real line, the Poisson process, both homogeneous or inhomogeneous, is sometimes interpreted as a counting process, and the notation $\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}$ is used to represent the Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Another reason for varying notation is due to the theory of point processes, which has a couple of mathematical interpretations.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, a simple Poisson point process may be considered as a random set, which suggests the notation $\textstyle x\in N$ , implying that $\textstyle x$ is a random point belonging to or being an element of the Poisson point process $\textstyle N$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] These different interpretations results in notation being used from mathematical fields such as measure theory and set theory.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the set theory and integral or measure theory notation can be used interchangeably.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] demonstrates two different ways to write a summation over a point process (see also Campbell's theorem (probability)).
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] More specifically, the integral notation on the left-hand side is interpreting the point process as a random counting measure while the sum on the right-hand side suggests a random set interpretation.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In probability theory, operations are applied to random variables for different purposes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Sometimes these operations are regular expectations that produce the average or variance of a random variable.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Others, such as characteristic functions (or Laplace transforms) of a random variable can be used to uniquely identify or characterize random variables and prove results like the central limit theorem.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In the theory of point processes there exist analogous mathematical tools which usually exist in the forms of measures and functionals instead of moments and functions respectively.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] One version of Campbell's theorem involves the Laplace functional of the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The probability generating function of non-negative integer-valued random variable leads to the probability generating functional being defined analogously with respect to any non-negative bounded function $\textstyle v$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ such that $\textstyle 0\leq v(x)\leq 1$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where the product is performed for all the points in ${\textstyle N}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] If the intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ of $\textstyle {N}$ is locally finite, then the ${\textstyle G}$ is well-defined for any measurable function $\textstyle u$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ is the length, area or volume (or more generally, the Lebesgue measure) of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The Mecke equation characterizes the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Let $\mathbb {N} _{\sigma }$ be the space of all $\sigma$ -finite measures on some general space ${\mathcal {Q}}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B_{i}|$ is the length, area, or volume (or more generally, the Lebesgue measure) of $\textstyle B_{i}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] Simple point processes are completely characterized by their void probabilities.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, complete information of a simple point process is captured entirely in its void probabilities, and two simple point processes have the same void probabilities if and if only if they are the same point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] The case for Poisson process is sometimes known as **Rényi’s theorem**, which is named after Alfréd Rényi who discovered the result for the case of a homogeneous point process in one dimension.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p01] then $\textstyle N$ is a Poisson point process with intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Mathematical operations can be performed on point processes to get new point processes and develop new mathematical models for the locations of certain objects.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] One example of an operation is known as thinning which entails deleting or removing the points of some point process according to a rule, creating a new process with the remaining points (the deleted points also form a point process).
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] For the Poisson process, the independent $\textstyle p(x)$ -thinning operations results in another Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] This thinning result of the Poisson point process is sometimes known as **Prekopa's theorem**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The two separate Poisson point processes formed respectively from the removed and kept points are stochastically independent of each other.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, if a region is known to contain $\textstyle n$ kept points (from the original Poisson point process), then this will have no influence on the random number of removed points in the same region.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] This ability to randomly create two independent Poisson point processes from one is sometimes known as *splitting* the Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, any points located in any of the point processes $\textstyle N_{1},N_{2}\dots$ will also be located in the superposition of these point processes $\textstyle {N}$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, the union of two (or countably more) Poisson processes is another Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The operation clustering is performed when each point $\textstyle x$ of some point process $\textstyle {N}$ is replaced by another (possibly different) point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] If the original process $\textstyle {N}$ is a Poisson point process, then the resulting process $\textstyle {N}_{c}$ is called a Poisson cluster point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] A mathematical model may require randomly moving points of a point process to other locations on the underlying mathematical space, which gives rise to a point process operation known as displacement or translation.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] One version of the displacement theorem involves a Poisson point process $\textstyle {N}$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ with intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, after each random and independent displacement of points, the original Poisson point process still exists.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The displacement theorem can be extended such that the Poisson points are randomly displaced from one Euclidean space $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ to another Euclidean space $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d'}$ , where $\textstyle d'\geq 1$ is not necessarily equal to $\textstyle d$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Another property that is considered useful is the ability to map a Poisson point process from one underlying space to another space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] If the mapping (or transformation) adheres to some conditions, then the resulting mapped (or transformed) collection of points also form a Poisson point process, and this result is sometimes referred to as the **mapping theorem**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The theorem involves some Poisson point process with mean measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ on some underlying space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] If the locations of the points are mapped (that is, the point process is transformed) according to some function to another underlying space, then the resulting point process is also a Poisson point process but with a different mean measure $\textstyle \Lambda '$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] with no atoms, where $\textstyle B$ is a Borel set and $\textstyle f^{-1}$ denotes the inverse of the function $\textstyle f$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] If $\textstyle {N}$ is a Poisson point process, then the new process $\textstyle {N}'$ is also a Poisson point process with the intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda '$ .
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The tractability of the Poisson process means that sometimes it is convenient to approximate a non-Poisson point process with a Poisson one.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The overall aim is to approximate both the number of points of some point process and the location of each point by a Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] There a number of methods that can be used to justify, informally or rigorously, approximating the occurrence of random events or phenomena with suitable Poisson point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The more rigorous methods involve deriving upper bounds on the probability metrics between the Poisson and non-Poisson point processes, while other methods can be justified by less formal heuristics.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] One method for approximating random events or phenomena with Poisson processes is called the **clumping heuristic**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The general heuristic or principle involves using the Poisson point process (or Poisson distribution) to approximate events, which are considered rare or unlikely, of some stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In some cases these rare events are close to being independent, hence a Poisson point process can be used.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method is a mathematical technique originally developed for approximating random variables such as Gaussian and Poisson variables, which has also been applied to point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method can be used to derive upper bounds on probability metrics, which give way to quantify how different two random mathematical objects vary stochastically.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Upperbounds on probability metrics such as total variation and Wasserstein distance have been derived.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Researchers have applied Stein's method to Poisson point processes in a number of ways, such as using Palm calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Techniques based on Stein's method have been developed to factor into the upper bounds the effects of certain point process operations such as thinning and superposition.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method has also been used to derive upper bounds on metrics of Poisson and other processes such as the Cox point process, which is a Poisson process with a random intensity measure.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In general, when an operation is applied to a general point process the resulting process is usually not a Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] For example, if a point process, other than a Poisson, has its points randomly and independently displaced, then the process would not necessarily be a Poisson point process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Such convergence work is directly related to the results known as the Palm–Khinchin equations, which has its origins in the work of Conny Palm and Aleksandr Khinchin, and help explains why the Poisson process can often be used as a mathematical model of various random phenomena.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson point process can be generalized by, for example, changing its intensity measure or defining on more general mathematical spaces.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] These generalizations can be studied mathematically as well as used to mathematically model or represent physical phenomena.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson-type random measures (PT) are a family of three random counting measures which are closed under restriction to a subspace, i.e. closed under Point process operation#Thinning.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] These random measures are examples of the mixed binomial process and share the distributional self-similarity property of the Poisson random measure.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] They are the only members of the canonical non-negative power series family of distributions to possess this property and include the Poisson distribution, negative binomial distribution, and binomial distribution.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson random measure is independent on disjoint subspaces, whereas the other PT random measures (negative binomial and binomial) have positive and negative covariances.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The PT random measures are discussed and include the Poisson random measure, negative binomial random measure, and binomial random measure.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In general, the concept of distance is of practical interest for applications, while topological structure is needed for Palm distributions, meaning that point processes are usually defined on mathematical spaces with metrics.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Furthermore, a realization of a point process can be considered as a counting measure, so points processes are types of random measures known as random counting measures.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] In this context, the Poisson and other point processes have been studied on a locally compact second countable Hausdorff space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] A **Cox point process**, **Cox process** or **doubly stochastic Poisson process** is a generalization of the Poisson point process by letting its intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ to be also random and independent of the underlying Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The process is named after David Cox who introduced it in 1955, though other Poisson processes with random intensities had been independently introduced earlier by Lucien Le Cam and Maurice Quenouille.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The intensity measure may be a realization of random variable or a random field.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] For example, if the logarithm of the intensity measure is a Gaussian random field, then the resulting process is known as a *log Gaussian Cox process*.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] More generally, the intensity measures is a realization of a non-negative locally finite random measure.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] Cox point processes exhibit a *clustering* of points, which can be shown mathematically to be larger than those of Poisson point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The generality and tractability of Cox processes has resulted in them being used as models in fields such as spatial statistics and wireless networks.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] For a given point process, each random point of a point process can have a random mathematical object, known as a **mark**, randomly assigned to it.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] These marks can be as diverse as integers, real numbers, lines, geometrical objects or other point processes.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The pair consisting of a point of the point process and its corresponding mark is called a marked point, and all the marked points form a **marked point process**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] It is often assumed that the random marks are independent of each other and identically distributed, yet the mark of a point can still depend on the location of its corresponding point in the underlying (state) space.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] If the underlying point process is a Poisson point process, then the resulting point process is a **marked Poisson point process**.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] If a general point process is defined on some mathematical space and the random marks are defined on another mathematical space, then the marked point process is defined on the Cartesian product of these two spaces.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] where $\textstyle B\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ is a Borel measurable set.
[src:stochastic-processes/poisson-point-process-p02] The failure process with the exponential smoothing of intensity functions (FP-ESI) is an extension of the nonhomogeneous Poisson process.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] A **stochastic differential equation** (**SDE**) is a differential equation in which one or more of the terms is a stochastic process, resulting in a solution which is also a stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs have many applications throughout pure mathematics and are used to model various behaviours of stochastic models such as prices of listed company shares, random growth models or physical systems that are subjected to thermal fluctuations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs have a random differential that is in the most basic case random white noise calculated as the distributional derivative of a Brownian motion or more generally a semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] However, other types of random behaviour are possible, such as jump processes like Lévy processes or semimartingales with jumps.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Stochastic differential equations are in general neither differential equations nor random differential equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Random differential equations are conjugate to stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Stochastic differential equations can also be extended to differential manifolds.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Some of these early examples were linear stochastic differential equations, also called Langevin equations after French physicist Langevin, describing the motion of a harmonic oscillator subject to a random force.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The mathematical theory of stochastic differential equations was developed in the 1940s through the groundbreaking work of Japanese mathematician Kiyosi Itô, who introduced the concept of stochastic integral and initiated the study of nonlinear stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Another approach was later proposed by Russian physicist Stratonovich, leading to a calculus similar to ordinary calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The most common form of SDEs in the literature is an ordinary differential equation with the right hand side perturbed by a term dependent on a white noise variable.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In most cases, SDEs are understood as continuous time limit of the corresponding stochastic difference equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] This understanding of SDEs is ambiguous and must be complemented by a proper mathematical definition of the corresponding integral.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Such a mathematical definition was first proposed by Kiyosi Itô in the 1940s, leading to what is known today as the Itô calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Another construction was later proposed by Russian physicist Stratonovich, leading to what is known as the Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The Itô integral and Stratonovich integral are related, but different, objects and the choice between them depends on the application considered.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The Itô calculus is based on the concept of non-anticipativeness or causality, which is natural in applications where the variable is time.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] An alternative view on SDEs is the stochastic flow of diffeomorphisms.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] This understanding is unambiguous and corresponds to the Stratonovich version of the continuous time limit of stochastic difference equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Associated with SDEs is the Smoluchowski equation or the Fokker–Planck equation, an equation describing the time evolution of probability distribution functions.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The generalization of the Fokker–Planck evolution to temporal evolution of differential forms is provided by the concept of stochastic evolution operator.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In physical science, there is an ambiguity in the usage of the term "Langevin SDEs".
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] While Langevin SDEs can be of a more general form, this term typically refers to a narrow class of SDEs with gradient flow vector fields.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] This class of SDEs is particularly popular because it is a starting point of the Parisi–Sourlas stochastic quantization procedure, leading to a N=2 supersymmetric model closely related to supersymmetric quantum mechanics.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] From the physical point of view, however, this class of SDEs is not very interesting because it never exhibits spontaneous breakdown of topological supersymmetry, i.e., (overdamped) Langevin SDEs are never chaotic.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Brownian motion or the Wiener process was discovered to be exceptionally complex mathematically.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The Wiener process is almost surely nowhere differentiable; thus, it requires its own rules of calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] There are two dominating versions of stochastic calculus, the Itô stochastic calculus and the Stratonovich stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Each of the two has advantages and disadvantages, and newcomers are often confused whether the one is more appropriate than the other in a given situation.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Guidelines exist (e.g. Øksendal, 2003) and conveniently, one can readily convert an Itô SDE to an equivalent Stratonovich SDE and back again.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Still, one must be careful which calculus to use when the SDE is initially written down.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Numerical methods for solving stochastic differential equations include the Euler–Maruyama method, Milstein method, Runge–Kutta method (SDE), Rosenbrock method, and methods based on different representations of iterated stochastic integrals.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In physics, SDEs have wide applicability ranging from molecular dynamics to neurodynamics and to the dynamics of astrophysical objects.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] More specifically, SDEs describe all dynamical systems, in which quantum effects are either unimportant or can be taken into account as perturbations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs can be viewed as a generalization of the dynamical systems theory to models with noise.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] This is an important generalization because real systems cannot be completely isolated from their environments and for this reason always experience external stochastic influence.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] There are standard techniques for transforming higher-order equations into several coupled first-order equations by introducing new unknowns.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] If X is a linear space and g are constants, the system is said to be subject to additive noise, otherwise it is said to be subject to multiplicative noise.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] For additive noise, the Itô and Stratonovich forms of the SDE generate the same solution, and it is not important which definition is used to solve the SDE.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] For multiplicative noise SDEs the Itô and Stratonovich forms of the SDE are different, and care should be used in mapping between them.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] For a fixed configuration of noise, SDE has a unique solution differentiable with respect to the initial condition.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Nontriviality of stochastic case shows up when one tries to average various objects of interest over noise configurations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In this sense, an SDE is not a uniquely defined entity when noise is multiplicative and when the SDE is understood as a continuous time limit of a stochastic difference equation.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In this case, SDE must be complemented by what is known as "interpretations of SDE" such as Itô or a Stratonovich interpretations of SDEs.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Nevertheless, when SDE is viewed as a continuous-time stochastic flow of diffeomorphisms, it is a uniquely defined mathematical object that corresponds to Stratonovich approach to a continuous time limit of a stochastic difference equation.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In physics, the main method of solution is to find the probability distribution function as a function of time using the equivalent Fokker–Planck equation (FPE).
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation is a deterministic partial differential equation.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] It tells how the probability distribution function evolves in time similarly to how the Schrödinger equation gives the time evolution of the quantum wave function or the diffusion equation gives the time evolution of chemical concentration.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] Alternatively, numerical solutions can be obtained by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The notation used in probability theory (and in many applications of probability theory, for instance in signal processing with the filtering problem and in mathematical finance) is slightly different.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] It is also the notation used in publications on numerical methods for solving stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] This notation makes the exotic nature of the random function of time $\xi ^{\alpha }$ in the physics formulation more explicit.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] In strict mathematical terms, $\xi ^{\alpha }$ cannot be chosen as an ordinary function, but only as a generalized function.
[src:stochastic-processes/stochastic-differential-equation] The mathematical formulation treats this complication with less ambiguity than the physics formulation.
